      <hedline>
        <hl1>Even More Mired Than Jerusalem</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Carl Birman letter says a mobilization of Jewish, Christian and Muslim leaders is needed to articulate a vision of how holy city of Jerusalem can be shared (July 31 Bernard Avishai Op-Ed)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Bernard Avishai (Op-Ed, July 31) seems as willing to ignore or overlook religious principles as the political leaders whose failures at Camp David he criticizes.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Bernard Avishai (Op-Ed, July 31) seems as willing to ignore or overlook religious principles as the political leaders whose failures at Camp David he criticizes.</p>
        <p>Jerusalem is a special place, and no amount of political arm-twisting or salesmanship can change that. Thus, Mr. Avishai's proposal to involve business and political leaders in Europe does not go far enough.</p>
        <p>What is needed is a mobilization by leaders of all the great religions of the world, especially Judaism, Christianity and Islam. Only these figures can articulate a vision of how this great and holy city can and must be shared in the years ahead.</p>
        <p>CARL BIRMAN  Brooklyn, July 31, 2000</p>
      </block>
